{[%evp 0,5,17,20,27,-4,-4,-4] Chigorin never met Reti over the board. The
Russian player passed away in 1908 when Reti just started to participate in
important tournaments. However, their ideas can lash, as this database clearly
shows.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 {The main Reti Opening move order can be quite
irritating, depending on the repertoire of the player with black. In most
lines, it is almost impossible to force White to deviate from his flexible
setup, based on a later d2-d3 and an attack against the centre with either
c2-c4 or e2-e4. Things would become more concrete and easier to handle with
black if White was induced to play d2-d4. As long as Black did not play ...
e7-e6 in the meantime, this would not transpose to a Catalan. If Black
maintains the possibility of developing his light-squared bishop actively, he
combination between g2-g3 and d2-d4 tends to be harmless.} Nc6 $5 {This move,
typical for the Chigorin Defence, seems to be the best solution of the complex
problem posed above. The principled answer is:} 3. d4 {when Black achieves
his first aim.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "LINE 1 3.d4 Bf5"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D02"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "36"]
[SourceVersionDate "2021.09.23"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 {Black has achieved his first aim. White has agreed
on combining the fianchetto with d2-d4, in a moment when the h3-c8 diagonal is
free still. On the other hand, Black still needs to justify the knight's
development to c6. Unlike in the genuine Chigorin opening, White has not
played c2-c4 yet, making the latent pressure on d4 sterile, at least at this
stage.} Bf5 {According to my analysis, this is the most effective way of
developing the bishop. Black's main idea is to cause White certain queenside
discomfort with ...Nb4. Besides that, f5 is not a bad square for the bishop in
general.} (3... Bg4 {is more speculative, aiming at starting tactical
complications. According to my analysis, White should be able to retain a
palpable plus.}) 4. a3 {White prepares c2-c4 without allowing ...Nb4. This is
a slow plan and it actually means heading for a Chigorin type of position
after wasting a tempo.} ({Chasing the bishop is a bit premature.} 4. Nh4 Be4 $5
5. f3 Bg6 6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. Bg2 (7. f4 e6 8. Bg2 Nf6 9. c3 Ne7 {yields Black
good stability on light squares.}) 7... Qd6 8. f4 {Taking measures against ...
e7-e5. Due to the latent pressure on d4, White is not ready for c2-c4 yet.}
O-O-O (8... Nf6 $5 9. Qd3 Ne4 10. c3 f5 $11) 9. c3 g5 $5 {A courageous way of
playing against a World champion.} 10. Qd3 (10. fxg5 Rxh2 11. Bf4 Rxh1+ 12.
Bxh1 e5 13. dxe5 Qe6 {with excellent play}) 10... Kb8 11. fxg5 e5 12. O-O e4 (
12... f6 $5) 13. Qe3 (13. Rxf7 $2 {was a typical blunder for blindfolded chess.
} exd3 {0-1 Karpov,A (2735)-Sadler,M (2650) Monte Carlo 1998}) 13... f6 $13 {
Black is better developed and his pressure against the enemy kingside
compensates for the pawn.}) (4. c3 {is more passive than the main line. After
the later c3-c4, ...Nb4 would be available anyway.} e6 5. Bg2 Be7 {Now is the
first moment when we see this way of developing the kingside. For the time
being, Black prevents Nh4. Depending on the circumstances, he will continue
with either ...h7-h6 or ...Nf6.} 6. O-O (6. Nbd2 h6 7. Ne5 Nf6 8. Qa4 a5 {
preparing ...Ra6} 9. Nxc6 Qd7 $1 10. O-O Qxc6 11. Qxc6+ bxc6 $11 {Since White
cannot block the double pawns, they actually ensure Black good control in the
centre.}) 6... Nf6 7. Nbd2 (7. Nh4 Be4 8. f3 Bxb1 9. Rxb1 Nh5) 7... h6 8. b4
O-O 9. Nb3 Ne4 {Black does not have problems in the static positions where
White refrains from c4.} 10. Bd2 a5 11. b5 Nb8 12. a4 Nd7 13. Qc1 Nb6 $15 {
Kunte,A (2491)-Carlsen,M (2838) Chess.com INT 2017 (0-1, 44)}) (4. c4 {is
examined in Line 2.}) (4. Bg2 {is the subject of Line 3 onwards.}) 4... e6 5.
Bg2 Be7 6. O-O (6. c4 Nf6 7. Nc3 Ne4 {is likely to transpose to the main line.}
) 6... Nf6 $1 {Now is a good moment for developing the knight, without wasting
time on ...h7-h6. The point is that after having wasted a tempo on a2-a3,
White is best advised to refrain from early bishop hunting.} 7. c4 (7. Nh4 $6
Bg4 $1 $146 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 g5 $1 {Suddenly, White's delay in development
causes him serious kingside problems.} 10. Bxg5 (10. Nf3 Bg6 11. Bxg5 h5 {
with dangerous initiative.}) 10... Nxg4 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. hxg4 Qxh4 13. gxh5
Rg8 14. f4 O-O-O {with a very strong attack for the sacrificed piece.}) 7...
O-O 8. Nc3 (8. Nh4 $6 {runs into} Be4 9. f3 Bxb1 $1 {leaving the knight
misplaced on h4 and the centre vulnerable after ...dxc4.}) 8... Ne4 {White can
forget about Nh4 now.} (8... dxc4 {is also possible, aiming at obtaining the
control over the central light squares.} 9. Qa4 Nd5 {I prefer the strategic
plan over pawn grabbing. The latter is viable, but offers White some sort of
pleasant compensation, in the spirit of the Catalan opening.} (9... Nxd4 10.
Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Bxb7 Rab8 12. Be3 $44 {Woods,C (1934)-Kett,T (2247) Liverpool
2008 (0-1, 32)}) 10. Qxc4 Nxc3 {Same issue as before.} (10... Nb6 {Montgomery,
R-Kopec,D corr 1990 (0-1, 16)} 11. Qa2 $1 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Be3 Qc4 14.
Bxb7 $13 {In this line, it is important that the white queen is defended.}) 11.
bxc3 (11. Qxc3 Be4 12. Be3 Qd5 {does not change much.}) 11... Be4 12. Qa2 Na5 {
with good play on light squares.}) 9. cxd5 {Anticipating ...dxc4.} exd5 10. Nd2
(10. Qb3 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 a5 12. Bf4 a4 $11 {as played in a few games, yields
Black comfortable play.}) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Na5 12. a4 Re8 13. Re1 Rc8 14.
Nb3 Nc4 15. Nd2 Na5 16. Nb3 c6 17. Nxa5 Qxa5 18. Qb3 Bf6 $11 {Roos,D (2420)
-Sadler,M (2665) Germany 1998 (0-1, 33)} *

