1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. c4 $5 {This is the most desirable approach
from a strategic point of view. If White could play like this without any
drawbacks, Black's developing system would be pointless. However, due to the
bishop's presence on f5, the main line below implies material sacrifices with
unclear consequences.} e6 {Before launching the counterattack, Black has to
take b4 under control.} (4... Nb4 $2 {is premature due to} 5. Qa4+) 5. Bg2 (5.
a3 {transposes to Line 1.}) 5... Nb4 6. O-O {The most principled continuation,
maintaining the pieces on the right trajectories.} (6. Na3 {avoids material
losses but places the knight on a very passive square.} Be7 7. O-O c6 8. Bd2
a5 9. c5 h5 $5 {This kind of move illustrates Black's possibilities in this
system.} ({However, the more natural} 9... Nf6 {is a simpler way to equality.}
10. Qb3 b6 11. Bxb4 $6 axb4 12. Qxb4 {Uzlavataya,A (2051)-Osmolny,V (2211)
Minsk 2018 (0-1, 31)} bxc5 $146 13. dxc5 Ne4 14. Rfc1 O-O {with fantastic
compensation for the pawn.}) 10. Qb3 ({The structure arising after} 10. h4 Nf6
{tends to favour Black, whose kingside minor pieces enjoy higher safety than
before the rook pawn moves.}) 10... h4 11. Bxb4 axb4 12. Qxb4 hxg3 13. fxg3 (
13. hxg3 Qc7 14. Nb1 g5 {with consistent initiative. Black controls many
squares and can create threats along the h-file.}) 13... Qc7 (13... b5 $2 {
only wastes time and offers White a target on c6.} 14. Ne5 $18 {Piket,M (2350)
-Van Dongen,C Netherlands 1992 (1-0, 20)}) 14. Ne5 Nf6 15. Qc3 (15. Nb1 Ng4 16.
Nxg4 Bxg4 17. e3 f5 18. Nd2 Bf6 {White's vulnerable structure blocked on dark
squares yields Black good counterplay.}) 15... O-O {Defending f7 before
occupying e4.} 16. Nc2 Ne4 {with obvious compensation for Black.}) 6... Nc2 7.
cxd5 (7. Nh4 {is the main alternative.} Nxa1 8. Nxf5 exf5 {WHite will have a
pawn for the exchange and a solid centre. However, Black has a few tempi
available for organising his counterplay.} 9. Nc3 (9. cxd5 {is likely to
transpose.}) 9... Qd7 $5 $146 {A flexible move order, inviting White to commit
himself in the centre.} (9... Nf6 {is not really wrong, though.} 10. cxd5 Be7
11. Bf4 O-O 12. Qd3 Qd7 13. Rxa1 c6 $6 {I would probably avoid that, even
though the position remains unclear.} 14. dxc6 bxc6 {Roiz,M (2630)-Heberla,B 
(2484) Port Erin 2007 (1-0, 38)}) 10. cxd5 (10. Nxd5 c6 11. Nc3 Nf6 {does not
bother Black.}) 10... Bb4 $1 {Starting to undermine d5.} 11. Qd3 Ne7 {The
the position remains double-edged. The pawn on d5 is in some danger and White
still needs two tempi to grab the errant knight.}) 7... Nxa1 {Black is a rook
up and the knight is ready to hurry back to his colleagues...} 8. e4 $1 {
An essential move, yielding White a tempo for his development and opening the
e-file.} (8. dxe6 fxe6 {transposes below after} 9. e4) 8... Bxe4 9. dxe6 fxe6
10. Nc3 Bxf3 $5 (10... Bf5 {is also possible.} 11. Nh4 Nf6 $1 $146 {
Development above anything.} 12. Nxf5 exf5 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Re1+ Kf7 15. Ba6 g6
16. Bf4 Kg7 17. Qxa1 Bd6 {White has adequate compensation for the exchange,
but Black is not in danger, either.}) 11. Bxf3 Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Preparing to
castle long, which would defend the queenside and set up pressure on d4.} 12.
Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bg2 Nf6 14. Qe2 Bb4 $5 $146 {The most active move, displaying
some ambitions in the centre.} (14... Be7 15. Bf4 (15. Bh3 Rb6 16. Bf4 {
may be more molesting.}) 15... O-O 16. Rxa1 Nd5 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Rc1 {Ding,L 
(2791)-Caruana, F (2835) chess24.com INT 2020 (½-½, 35) Optically, White
retains some pressure, but Black could shatter this illusion with} Rxf4 $5 $146
19. gxf4 Rf8 {with comfortable equality.}) 15. Bf4 (15. Bg5 O-O 16. Rxa1 h6 {
is no big improvement, as the bishop does not have comfortable squares to
retreat to.}) (15. Bh3 Rb6) 15... O-O 16. Rxa1 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nd5 {From a static
point of view, White's position looks appealing, but Black has dynamic play.
Chances are about equal and the position remains unclear.} *

