1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 {White continues developing naturally,
ignoring Black's threats.} Nb4 $1 {An important resource for Black in this
system. The last move prevents White's natural queenside development.} (4... e6
5. O-O Be7 (5... Nb4 6. Ne1 $1) 6. c4 Nf6 7. Nc3 $14) 5. Na3 {A curious
situation. The knight on a3 is misplaced, but the black knight is unstable on
b4. Play has deviated from the natural patterns and it is early to decide
which side has made higher concessions.} e6 6. O-O Be7 7. c3 {The most common
continuation.} (7. c4 {transposes to Line 1.}) (7. Ne5 {is examined in Line 5.}
) 7... Nc6 {The knight has retu7rned on its previous square, but now White
faces the positional threat ...Bxa3.} 8. Qa4 {An active move, preparing a
queenside attack.} (8. Nc2 {is solid, but a bit slow. Besides, it does not
challenge Black's control over e4.} Nf6 9. Nce1 (9. Nh4 Be4 10. f3 Bxc2 11.
Qxc2 Nh5 $5 $15) 9... h6 10. Nd3 O-O 11. Bf4 Ne4 {Black does not have problems
i this static position.} 12. Nd2 (12. h3 a5 13. a4 Bd6 14. Qc1 Bxf4 15. Qxf4
Qd6 16. Rfd1 Qxf4 17. Nxf4 Nd6 18. Nd3 {Mikhalevski,V (2552)-Lortkipanidze,N 
(2416) Lichess.org INT 2021 (0-1, 60)} Nb8 19. b3 c6 $11) 12... Nd6 (12... Nxd2
13. Qxd2 Bd6 $11) (12... g5 13. Be3 Nd6 $11 {prevents the paln of an early
e2-e4.}) 13. f3 (13. Re1 $5 a5 $5 {Just an useful half-waiting move.} 14. e4
Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Rxe4 Qd5 18. Qe2 Bd6 $11) 13... Bxd3 14.
exd3 Nf5 15. Qe2 Qd7 16. Rae1 Rae8 $11 17. g4 $2 Bh4 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Qd1 Bxe1
20. Rxe1 g5 21. Bg3 f4 $15 {Silva,L (2374)-Ruck,R (2502) Pontevedra 2018 (0-1,
56)}) (8. c4 Bxa3 9. cxd5 exd5 10. bxa3 Nge7 $11) (8. Qb3 {is examined in Line
4.}) (8. Nb1 {funnily transposes to 4.c3 in Line 1.}) 8... Qd7 9. b4 (9. Nb5 $5
$146 {creates a series of concrete possibilities, but Black can deal with all
the threats.} Rc8 (9... a6 $2 10. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 11. Nxc7+ $1) 10. c4 Nf6 (10...
h6 {is a bit too slow} 11. Rd1 a6 12. Nc3 Nf6 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qxa4 15.
Nxa4 Nd7 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Bxd5 c6 18. Bg2 Nxe5 {The position remains slightly
more pleasant for White.}) 11. Ne5 (11. Nh4 Nxd4 $1) (11. Rd1 Ne4 $1 $11) (11.
Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Rfd1 O-O $11) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Ne4 13. Qxa7 c6 14.
Nc3 (14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15. Nc3 Bf5 {yields Black obvious compensation due to his
strong light-squared bishop.}) 14... Bc5 15. Qa5 b6 16. Qa4 Nxc3 17. bxc3 b5
18. cxb5 cxb5 19. Qb3 O-O {White's extra pawn does not make itself felt yet
and Black's structure is better. Besides, he is more active, too. For
instance, the bishop on f5 is more active than its rival on g2. Black has good
compensation.}) (9. Re1 $5 Nf6 (9... h6 {is worth mentioning, since White's
last move does not change the dynamic balance.}) 10. Bg5 (10. Nh4 $6 Bg4 11. h3
Bh5 12. g4 $2 Ne4 $17) 10... Be4 $5 (10... a6 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4
$14 {Svane,R (2613)-Bluebaum,M (2647) Playchess.com INT 2020 (1-0, 57)}) 11.
Nb1 h6 12. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 13. Nbd2 f5 {Black does not have problems. In fact, he
has good control over the centre. White does not have the time to threaten
with trapping the bishop, thus inducing the exchange on f3:} 14. Bf1 $6 h5 $15
15. h4 (15. Red1 h4 $17 {and Ne1 will arrive too late.}) 15... f4 $1 16. gxf4
Rg8+ 17. Kh2 Rg4 $17) 9... Ne5 $1 $146 {Immediately freeing Black.} 10. Qxd7+ (
10. Qb3 Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 a5 (11... Nf6) 12. bxa5 Rxa5 13. c4 c6 14. Nc2 Nf6 $15)
10... Nxd7 {Black's development is more harmonious.} *

