1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qb3
{This is the most harmonious way of continuing the development. Besides, it
gains a tempo by attacking b7.} Rb8 9. Bf4 Nf6 10. c4 (10. Nh4 {is ineffective.
} Bg4 11. f3 Bh5 12. g4 O-O $5 13. gxh5 Nxh5) 10... O-O {White has reached
some sort of Catalan setup, but his development is not optimal. The main
drawback of his setup consists of the fact that the knight on a3 is far from
the squares e4 and d5, allowing Black to play for a comfortable blockade
on light squares.} (10... Be4 {is also possible.}) 11. Rfd1 (11. cxd5 Nxd5 $5 (
11... exd5 $11) 12. Bd2 Nb6 ({An improved version of the plan from the
following game:} 12... Be4 13. e3 Bxa3 14. Qxa3 Qf6 15. Nh4 {Svane,R (2839)
-Martirosyan,H (2981) Chess.com INT 2019 (1-0, 48)}) 13. Rfd1 Be4 14. e3 Bxa3
15. Qxa3 Qd5 {This is why the knight has cleared the square on d5 a few moves
earlier.} 16. Ne1 Bxg2 17. Nxg2 Rbd8 18. Bc3 Rd6 $11) (11. Nb5 $5 $146 dxc4 12.
Qxc4 Nd5 13. Ne5 (13. Bd2 a6 14. Nc3 Nb6 {wins the pawn on d4.}) 13... Na5 14.
Qc1 (14. Qa4 Nxf4 15. gxf4 c6 16. Nc3 f6 17. Nf3 b5 18. Qd1 Nc4 $132) 14...
Nxf4 15. gxf4 c6 16. Nc3 f6 17. Nf3 Nc4 18. Na4 Nd6 19. Nc5 b6 $13 {In these
lines, we ca feel that White is struggling to restore his optimal harmony.
Black can use the time needed by White to achieve that for weakening the
kingside and improving his own coordination, too.}) 11... Be4 12. Rac1 a6 13.
Ne5 (13. Qe3 Re8 $5) 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 dxc4 $5 $146 {After the bishops'
exchange, I find this plan to be the most consequent.} (14... Bd6 15. Qf3 Nb4 {
Radzhabov,R (2344)-Afanasiev,N (2514) Cheliabinsk 2021 (0-1, 52)}) 15. Qxc4 (
15. Nxc6 bxc6 {yields Black pressure along the b-file.} 16. Qc2 c3 $5 (16...
Bxa3 17. bxa3 Nd5 18. Bd2 Nb6 $11) 17. Qxc3 Nd5 18. Qc2 Nxf4+ 19. gxf4 Qd5+ 20.
Kg1 Bd6 21. e3 Qh5 $11) (15. Naxc4 Nxd4 {The white queen does not have optimal
squares.} 16. Qd3 (16. Qc3 c5 17. e3 Nd5 18. Qe1 Nf5 $15) 16... Nb5 (16... c5
17. e3 Nb5 18. Nd7 $1) 17. e4 Qxd3 18. Rxd3 Rfd8 {White may have compensation
for the pawn, but Black is in no danger.}) 15... Nd5 {With the knight passive
on a3, White cannot take advantage of his central activity. In certain cases,
it looks more like exposure than activity.} 16. Nb1 (16. Nxc6 Nxf4+ 17. gxf4
bxc6 18. Qc2 Bd6 19. e3 g5 $1 $132) 16... Bd6 17. Nd2 (17. Nc3 Nxf4+ 18. gxf4
Qh4) 17... Ncb4 18. a3 Nxf4+ 19. gxf4 Nd5 20. e3 f6 21. Nef3 Qe8 (21... b5 $5)
22. Kh1 Kh8 23. Rg1 Rg8 {With interesting play and mutual chances.} *

