1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 Bf5 4. Bg2 Nb4 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. Ne5 $5 {
The low popularity of this move must be caused by the poor practical results
achieved with it. However, White is likely to retain a small "Catalan plus"
against the main continuation rehearsed in practice. The main idea behind the
last move is to prevent ...Nc6.} f6 $5 $146 {After long hesitations, I came to
the conclusion that Black needs to react this way. Black weakens e6 a bit and
deviates from the natural course of development, but gains two tempi for
gaining control over many squares and even starting a kingside attack.} ({
The main line goes:} 7... Nf6 8. c3 Na6 9. Qb3 $1 (9. Nac4 $5 O-O 10. Ne3 Be4
11. f3 Bg6 12. Qb3 Rb8 $11) 9... Qc8 10. c4 c6 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Rac1 Rd8 13.
Rfd1 {White is fully mobilised. True, his knight on a3 still needs regrouping,
but the knight on a6 is also poorly placed. This is the main difference with
respect to the positions in Line 4.} h6 14. Nc2 (14. Nb1 Be4 15. Nd2 Bxg2 16.
Kxg2 Nc7 17. Qf3 Nce8 18. g4 $16 {Arsovic,Z (2421)-Ivanisevic,I (2658) Bar
2015 (0-1, 46)}) 14... Nc7 15. Ne1 (15. a3 $6 a5 16. Qa2 a4 $11 17. Bd2 Ne4 18.
Be1 Bf6 19. Nb4 c5 20. Nbd3 cxd4 21. cxd5 exd5 $17 {Nikolic,P (2655)
-Morozevich,A (2575) Moscow 1994 (½-½, 44)}) (15. g4 $5 {The pawn is taboo
since, after the exchange on g4, Qg3 would create a decisive double attack on
c7 and g4.} dxc4 16. Qg3 Bxc2 17. Rxc2 Nb5 18. Rxc4 Nd5 19. a4 Nxf4 20. Qxf4
Nd6 21. Rc3 $14) 15... Be4 (15... a5 16. g4 Bh7 17. Qg3 $16) {Kozak,A (2816)
-Egorov,E (2575) Chess.com INT 2020 (1-0, 52)} 16. Bxe4 Nxe4 17. c5 Re8 18. f3
Nf6 19. N1d3 $14) 8. Nf3 (8. Nd3 h5 $5 9. h4 a5 {leaves White a bit stuck.})
8... Nc6 $1 {Threatening ...Bxa3 with good control on light squares.} 9. Nb1 {
The most consistent answer, preparing c2-c4 followed by Nc3.} (9. Nb5 a6 10.
Nc3 {leaves White rigid in the centre.} Qd7 11. Re1 Be4 $5 (11... O-O-O $5 12.
e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 e5) 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nd2 f5 14. c3 g5 15. Nc4 h5 16. f3 h4 {
with excellent counterplay.}) (9. b3 h5 10. c4 g5 {is complex, but not without
chances for Black.}) 9... Qd7 10. c4 O-O-O {Black plays in the true spirit of
the Chigorin defence. Two extra tempi cannot harm.} 11. Be3 {Over defending d4.
} (11. Nc3 dxc4 12. Qa4 Kb8 13. Qxc4 Na5 14. Qb5 Qxb5 15. Nxb5 a6 16. Nc3 Bb4
17. e4 Bg4 18. Rd1 Ne7 $13) (11. c5 e5 $132) 11... Kb8 {Reinforcing the threat
...dxc4 (see below).} 12. a3 {Starting a slow pawn attack.} (12. Nc3 dxc4 13.
Qa4 $6 Nb4 $1 $15 {Now is when the king is useful on b8, since the pawn on a7
is defended.}) 12... h5 13. b4 (13. h4 g5 $1 14. hxg5 fxg5 15. Nxg5 Qe8 {
followed by ...Qg6 and ...h5-h4, with a very strong attack.}) (13. cxd5 exd5
14. b4 Bh3 15. Nc3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 h4 {also yields Black an attack, for instance}
17. Nxh4 g5 18. Nf3 Qh3+ 19. Kg1 g4 20. Nh4 Rxh4 21. gxh4 Bd6 $19) 13... h4 $5
{The position requires practical testing, but Black seems to be doing fine in
this almost irrational position.} (13... dxc4 $5 14. Nc3 Bd6 {is less
ambitious, but playable.}) 14. Nxh4 Be4 $1 15. Bxe4 (15. Nc3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 g5
17. Nf3 e5 {with initiative}) (15. Nf3 Nh6 16. Nbd2 Nf5 17. c5 g5 18. b5 Na5
19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Nd2 Nxe3 21. fxe3 f5 22. Qa4 b6 {White will soon have to
sacrifice on e4, as otherwise his bishop would be buried alive and his
kingside would be in danger. The position remains unclear}) 15... dxe4 16. Qa4
g5 {WHite has to work up some small miracles in order to avoid troubles.} 17.
d5 $1 exd5 18. cxd5 Qxd5 (18... Qh3 {is likely to lead to a draw by perpetual.}
19. dxc6 a6 20. cxb7 {White has won a piece, but Black has got a tempo to
start his own attack.} Rxh4 21. gxh4 Bd6 22. f4 exf3 23. Rxf3 Bxh2+ 24. Kf2
Qxh4+ 25. Kf1 Bg3 26. Rxg3 Qxg3 27. Bf2 Qh3+ {with a perpetual.}) 19. b5 Nd4
20. Bxd4 Qxd4 21. Qxd4 Rxd4 22. Nf5 Rd5 23. Nxe7 Nxe7 $11 *

