1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 {This move, refraining from fighting for space in
the centre, is an invitation to a reversed Pirc Defence.} e5 4. d3 (4. c4 $6 e4
{and}) (4. O-O e4 {are likely to leave White struggling with space.} 5. Ne1 Nf6
6. d3 Bf5) 4... Nf6 5. O-O Be7 {This position can be approached in various
ways. One can write a thin book on it since this is the Classical Pirc with
reversed colours, or just get some orientations. Pirc is one of my favourite
openings with black, but with reversed colours, I do not feel that White's
extra tempo promises him chances for an advantage. AT least not if Black plays
solidly. In many cases, ...e5-e4 either leads to simplifications or ensures
Black some space advantage.} 6. c4 (6. c3 O-O 7. Nbd2 (7. b4 e4 $1 {leaves the
white queenside a bit weak.}) (7. Qc2 e4 8. dxe4 Nxe4 $11 9. Nd4 Nxd4 10. cxd4
Bf5 11. Qb3 Qd7 {Dragomirescu,A (2235)-Rapport,J (2282) Belgrade 2018 (0-1, 65)
Neither player has problems.} 12. Qxb7 $2 Rfb8 13. Qa6 Rb6 14. Qd3 Nxg3 $1 15.
Qxg3 Rg6 $1 $19) 7... e4 (7... a5 8. Qc2 Be6 9. e4 dxe4 10. dxe4 h6 11. Rd1 Qb8
12. Nf1 a4 13. Be3 Rd8 $11) 8. Ne1 (8. dxe4 dxe4 9. Ng5 e3 10. fxe3 Ng4 $19)
8... Bf5 9. dxe4 dxe4 10. Nc2 Re8 11. Ne3 Bg6 $11) (6. Bg5 O-O 7. Nc3 Be6 8. e4
dxe4 {The main drawback of this system. Black can turn the position very dry
from an early stage. With opposite colours, such an approach would be not
satisfactory for White, of course.} 9. dxe4 h6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nd5 Nd4 12.
Nxd4 Bxd5 13. exd5 exd4 $11) (6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 dxe4 {AGain simple play.} 8.
dxe4 Bc5 9. c3 a5 10. Qc2 Qe7 11. Nc4 Rd8 12. Ne3 Be6 13. Ng5 $6 (13. b3 h6 14.
Nh4 Rd7 15. Nhf5 Qd8 $11 {[%cal Gc5f8] followed by ...Bf8, ...Kh7, ...g7-g6.})
13... Bxe3 14. Nxe6 (14. Bxe3 Bc4 $15) 14... Bxf2+) (6. a3 {was played in a
few games at a high level, but in blitz games through the internet.} O-O (6... a5
7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 e4 9. Ne5 e3 $36 {Svane,R (2613)-Carlsen,M (2863) Lichess.org
INT 2020 (0-1, 33)}) 7. Nc3 (7. b4 e4) 7... d4 8. Nb1 a5 9. a4 Be6 10. Bg5 Nd7
11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. c3 Nc5 13. Nfd2 Rad8 $15 {Grischuk,A (2777)-Karjakin,S (2752)
Lichess.org INT 2020 (½-½, 47)}) 6... O-O {The most consistent.} (6... d4 $6
{runs into} 7. b4 $1 {The extra tempo with respect to the Schmidt Benoni is
for once relevant.}) (6... dxc4 $5 7. dxc4 (7. Qa4 O-O 8. Qxc4 Be6 9. Qc2 Nd5 {
leads to an imperfect version of the reversed Dragon, since the queen has
wasted a few tempi without improving its placement.}) 7... O-O 8. Nc3 h6 $5 {
Preventing Ng5 and Bg5 and inviting White to show his cards.} 9. Qc2 Bg4 $5) 7.
cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3 Be6 $1 {Since White has spent a tempo on d2-d3, the break
with d3-d4 is not dangerous. We can compare this position to that arising in
the classical Dragon. White could have h2-h3 or Kh1 as an extra move, which
does not change the situation a lot. In our case, White can equalise at once,
but this is not his main dream.} 9. d4 (9. Bd2 {leads to more consistent play.
However, since he was not forced to retreat with his knight from the centre,
as in the English Dragon main lines, Black has no special problems. I have
advocated the Dragon side with reversed colours in my article on the Dragon,
but the perspective was different there. Black (the Dragon side) does not mind
having equal chances in complicated positions. The same applies to Black (the
Anti-Dragon side) in our current position.} Qd7 10. a3 f6 11. Rc1 (11. b4 a5 {
shows that White is incompletely developed.}) 11... Nxc3 12. Bxc3 a5 $11) 9...
exd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd5 (11. Qxd4 Bf6 {may be even more pleasant for Black.
}) 11... Bxd5 12. Qxd4 Bxg2 13. Qxd8 Rfxd8 14. Kxg2 $11 *

