1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. c4 {This is an invitation to the reversed Schmidt
Benoni, which Black should not decline.} d4 {In the proper Schmidt Benoni,
Black faces problems generating counterplay. White's extra tempo in the
position with reversed colours does not change much.} (3... dxc4 {is also
playable.}) 4. Bg2 (4. b4 {sacrifices a pawn for questionable compensation:}
Nxb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. Ne5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7) 4... e5 5. d3 {White should not
ignore the threat ...e5-e4.} (5. O-O $6 e4 6. Ne1 h5 $1 {yields Black
dangerous initiative.} 7. Bxe4 (7. d3 e3 8. fxe3 h4 9. exd4 Nxd4 10. e3 hxg3
11. hxg3 Nf5 $19 {Gareyev,T (2569)-Morozevich,A (2656) St Petersburg 2018 (0-1,
21)}) 7... Nf6 8. Bg2 (8. Bxc6+ {gains some time for the development, but
giving up this bishop is a high price to pay.} bxc6 9. Nf3 h4 10. d3 {0-1 (22)
Danielyan,V (2344)-Harutyunian,T (2513) Yerevan 2017} (10. Nxh4 Qd7 $19 {
followed by ...Qh3.}) 10... hxg3 11. fxg3 Ng4 $15 {White's extra pawn is
irrelevant and Black maintains constant pressure.}) 8... h4 9. d3 hxg3 10. hxg3
(10. fxg3 Bh3 11. Bxh3 (11. Rf2 $2 Ng4 $19 {Podzielny,K (2412)-Meister,J (2481)
playchess.com INT 2007 (0-1, 48)}) 11... Rxh3 12. Nd2 Qd7 $15) 10... Bg4 $1 {
Preparing ...Qd7/c8 followed by ...Bh3.} (10... Bh3 {allows White to gradually
neutralise Black's intiiative and retain a playable, though unpleasant,
position.} 11. Bxh3 Rxh3 12. Kg2 Qd7 13. Nf3 O-O-O 14. Rh1 Rxh1 15. Qxh1 Re8
$44 {Zubov,A (2627)-Harutyunian,T (2462) Yerevan 2016 (½-½, 81)}) 11. Nd2 Qd7
$15) 5... Bb4+ $1 {The most effective way of neutralising the importance of
White's extra tempo.} (5... Nf6 6. O-O {forces Black to delay his development
a bit.} a5 (6... Be7 7. b4 Bxb4 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Qa4+ Nc6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11.
Qxb4 $14) 7. e3 $5 {It is hard to claim an advantage for White, but using the
tempo wasted on ...a7-a5 for attacking the centre yields him certain activity.}
) (5... Bc5 6. O-O Nge7 {prevents b2-b4, but the knight stands a bit unnatural
on e7.} 7. Na3 O-O 8. Nc2) 6. Bd2 (6. Nbd2 a5 7. O-O Nf6 8. a3 Be7 9. b3 {
Preventing ...a5-a4.} O-O 10. Rb1 Re8 $1 {Indirectly defending e5 in order to
prevent b3-b4.} 11. Ne1 {The only way of preparing b3-b4.} Bf5 12. Nc2 Bf8 13.
b4 axb4 14. axb4 Qd7 15. b5 Nd8 16. Re1 {Kortschnoj,V-Lengyel,L Gyula 1965 
(½-½, 51)} c6 17. Nf3 h6 18. Rb3 Bc5 {with a stable position for Black.})
6... a5 7. O-O Nf6 8. Na3 O-O 9. Bxb4 {The fact that this seems to be the
engine's favourite speaks about the soundness of Black's plan.} (9. Nb5 Re8 10.
e3 Bf5 11. e4 Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 13. Bc1 Nd7 $17 {Speelman,J (2555)-Nakamura,H 
(2601) Port Erin 2004 (0-1, 47)}) (9. Nc2 Bxd2 $5 10. Qxd2 (10. Nxd2 Qd6 {
does not change much}) 10... Qd6 {Black has free development and can prepare ..
.e5-e4 by developing normally, ...Bf5, ...Rad8, ..Rfe8, maybe ...h7-h6}) (9.
Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 {AFter this exchange, breaking with e2-e3 becomes less
appealing.} 11. Nc2 Re8 12. a3 Bc5 13. Nd2 Bf8 14. b3 Bg4 (14... h5 15. h4 {
may favour White slightly with respect to the main line.} Bg4 16. Rb1 Nd8 17.
b4 axb4 18. axb4 c6 {Postny,E (2605)-Eljanov,P (2672) Chess.com INT 2021 (0-1,
55) Black is OK, but due to his relative control over g5 after Ne4, White
should not be unhappy.}) 15. h3 Bh5 16. Rb1 Nd8 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 {Gabuzyan,
H (2585)-Sargsyan,S (2601) Yerevan 2020 (½-½, 107)} c6 {With comfortable
play.}) 9... axb4 10. Nc2 Qe7 11. a3 {White should fight against Black's
queenside space advantage at once.} (11. Re1 Rd8 12. Qd2 {Gdanski,J (2518)-Van
Kampen,R (2618) Warsaw 2013 (½-½, 36)} h6 $5 {Preparing ...Bf5 without
fearing Nh4 and preventing Ng5-e4.} 13. e3 dxe3 14. Qxe3 Ng4 15. Qe2 Bf5 $15)
11... bxa3 12. Rxa3 Rxa3 13. Nxa3 h6 14. Nd2 Nb4 15. Qa4 Bd7 16. Qa7 Nc6 17.
Qa4 (17. Qxb7 Rb8 18. Qa6 (18. Qxc7 $2 Ne8 {traps the queen.}) 18... Rxb2 $15)
17... Nd8 18. Qb3 Bc6 19. Nc2 (19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Nc2 c5 $11 {strengthens
Black's centre.}) 19... Bxg2 20. Kxg2 c5 $11 {Petukhov,V (2040)-Douglas,S 
(2283) ICCF email 2008 (½-½, 27)} *

